at the radicals condemned in their liberal forebears. Camp Sites considers key themes of postwar culture, from the conflict between performance and authenticity to the rise of the meritocracy, through the lens of camp, the underground sensibility of pre-Stonewall gay life. In so doing, it argues that our basic assumptions about the social style of the postwar milieu are deeply informed by certain presuppositions about homosexual experience and identity, and that these presuppositions remain stubbornly entrenched despite our post-Stonewall consciousness-raising.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCamp (Style)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUniversities and collegesxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478663840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786638.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles